ymptoms that could indicate the occurrence of torsade de pointes such as dizziness, palpitations, or syncope.', 'Metabolism', 'Anastrozole, Aminoglutethimide, Letrozole, Fulvestrant, Abarelix, Flutamide, Relugolix, Bicalutamide, Degarelix, Nilutamide, Apalutamide, Exemestane', 'Phenelzine, Duloxetine, Tranylcypromine, Vilazodone, Desvenlafaxine, Isocarboxazid, Oxitriptan, Tryptophan, Vortioxetine, Milnacipran, Levomilnacipran, More', 'Major', NULL, 'DDInter', 'pharmacodynamic', NULL, 'https://ddinter2.scbdd.com/server/interact/142965/', '[1] "Product Information. Fareston (toremifene)." Schering Laboratories, Kenilworth, NJ.[2] "Product Information. Fareston (toremifene)." Schering Laboratories, Kenilworth, NJ.[3] Therapeutic Research Faculty "Natural Medicines Comprehensive Database. Available from: URL: http://www.naturaldatabase.com." ([1995-2008...]):[4] Wohlt PD, Zheng L, Gunderson S, Balzar SA, Johnson BD, Fish JT "Recommendations for the use of medications with continuous enteral nutrition." Am J Health Syst Pharm 66 (2009): 1438-67[5] "Product Information. VFEND (voriconazole)." Pfizer U.S. Pharmaceuticals, New York, NY.', 1767369485);
